In the 1930s and 1940s Gagnier was active conducting for radio, beginning with a series of 26 concerts in 1931 with the Canadian Grenadier Guards Band for CBS Radio in the United States.

He himself earned a Doctor of Music from the Université de Montréal in 1934.
From 1927-1929 he conducted the Montreal Symphony Orchestra (no relation to the current orchestra of that name).
During the 1920s and 1930s, Gagnier worked frequently as a guest conductor throughout Canada and the United States, notably working on a number occasions with the famous Goldman Band.
In 1911-1912 Gagnier played in the orchestra and served as assistant conductor for the Montreal Opera Company.

His compositions are written in a wide variety of styles from romanticism to impressionism to 20th century idioms.
